Diagnosis. This new species resembles
O. komurai
by having a crescent-shaped embolus and a similarly shaped bulb (see Figs 15C , 16C and fig. 3G in
Wang et al. 2012
), but the male can be distinguished by the long and clavate shaped TA ( vs absent, compare Fig. 16C with fig. 3G in
Wang et al. 2012
) and the triangular tip of the conductor ( vs the round tip, compare Fig. 16B–C with fig. 3F–G in
Wang et al . 2012
). The female can be distinguished by the short connecting tube ( vs long, compare Figs 15E–F , 16E–F with fig. 3H–I in
Wang et al. 2012
).
